This paper deals with the computability of probability measures and the limitations of randomized methods in producing samples without outliers. This topic is closely related to computational complexity (cs.CC) and data structures (cs.DS) as it involves analyzing the efficiency and effectiveness of algorithms for sampling. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of machine learning techniques (cs.LG, cs.AI) for sampling, which further supports these categories. Finally, the paper also touches on information theory (cs.IT) in its discussion of the limitations of compressing samples without losing information about outliers.
